[
    {
        "content": "<p>I was playing around with filters a bit (in Isabelle) and eventually realised that the answer to some of my questions was already in Mathlib. So I was wondering if the people on here could clarify one thing that I don't quite understand and couldn't find much about on the internet. I only have vague understanding of filters to be honest.</p>\n<p>The question is about the theorem <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/order/filter/at_top_bot.html#filter.tendsto_iff_seq_tendsto\">filter.tendsto_iff_seq_tendsto</a> in Mathlib, which states:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">filter</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">tendsto_of_seq_tendsto</span>\n<span class=\"w\">   </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u_3</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">β</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u_4</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">β</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">k</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">filter</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">l</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">filter</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">β</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">k</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">is_countably_generated</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">),</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">filter</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">tendsto</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">filter</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">at_top</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">k</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">filter</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">tendsto</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∘</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">filter</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">at_top</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">l</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">filter</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">tendsto</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">k</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">l</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>So basically, if you have a countably generated filter then its behaviour is completely characterised by convergence of sequences.</p>\n<p>What I'm wondering is: Does the converse also hold? I.e. is any filter that satisfies this countably generated? If not, is there a standard name for filters that have this property and what is an example of one that isn't countably generated?</p>",
        "id": 546860985,
        "sender_full_name": "Manuel Eberl",
        "timestamp": 1761301082
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Fwiw, you're pointing at lean3 code that's years out of date by now</p>",
        "id": 546861283,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1761301174
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Filter.tendsto_iff_seq_tendsto#doc\">docs#Filter.tendsto_iff_seq_tendsto</a> is the Lean4 version.</p>",
        "id": 546861638,
        "sender_full_name": "Christian Merten",
        "timestamp": 1761301302
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I would guess the converse doesn’t hold, and search internet for examples of sequential spaces that are not first countable, hoping to find inspiration for counter-examples.</p>",
        "id": 546871597,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Massot",
        "timestamp": 1761304782
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do you have any reason to ask or are you simply hoping to use more sequences and less filters? We can probably help if you want to become friends with filters.</p>",
        "id": 546871780,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Massot",
        "timestamp": 1761304848
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I have lectures notes about filters but they are in French.</p>",
        "id": 546871818,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Massot",
        "timestamp": 1761304860
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The original motivation was this: suppose I have a family of sets <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A(x)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> that \"converges\" to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x\\to F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> (for some filter <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span>). I also have a function that is Lebesgue-integrable on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>I wanted to show that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>lim</mi><mo>⁡</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mo>∫</mo><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></msub><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mtext> </mtext><mtext>d</mtext><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mo>∫</mo><mi>B</mi></msub><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mtext> </mtext><mtext>d</mtext><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lim_{x\\to F} \\int_{A(x)} f(t)\\,\\text{d}t = \\int_B f(t)\\,\\text{d}t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.3358em;vertical-align:-0.5308em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop\">lim</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">→</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1692em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.3442em;margin-left:-0.1945em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">A</span><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.5308em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">d</span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1608em;vertical-align:-0.3558em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1225em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.3442em;margin-left:-0.1945em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3558em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">d</span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span>.<br>\nWe have some versions of this for various filters <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> and various families of intervals <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>, but it's a mess. So I wanted to prove it once and for all for all sensible values of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>Capturing the notion that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A(x) \\to B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x\\to F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> is a bit strange as well. I don't think \"convergence of a family of sets to a set\" can be expressed as a filter (if it can, I'd be interested to hear how). I ended up doing it like this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Isabelle\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">definition</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">tendsto_set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">::</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"('a ⇒ 'b set) ⇒ 'b set ⇒ 'a filter ⇒ bool\"</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kp\">where</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"s\">\"tendsto_set A B F ⟷ eventually (λy. A y ⊆ B) F ∧ (∀x. eventually (λy. x ∈ A y ⟷ x ∈ B) F)\"</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>That works. But I don't think it can be expressed as a filter.</p>\n<p>Anyway, the fact I wanted to prove follows easily from dominated convergence, but we only have dominated convergence for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mtext>sequentially</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F = \\text{sequentially}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">sequentially</span></span></span></span></span>. So I investigated to see how to make this work for more general filters. I was able to show that it works for all countably generated filters.</p>\n<p>I did wonder, however, whether it makes sense to introduce a more general class of \"sequentially determined filters\" (or whatever you want to call them). In Isabelle it would be something like this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Isabelle\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">locale</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">sequential_filter</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"kp\">fixes</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">F</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">::</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"'a filter\"</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"kp\">assumes</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">approachable</span><span class=\"o\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"s\">\"(⋀f. filterlim f F sequentially ⟹ eventually (λn. P (f n)) sequentially) ⟹ eventually P F\"</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Clearly, every countably generated filter is \"sequentially determined\". Not sure if the converse holds, or if there are interesting filters that satisfy one but not the other.</p>",
        "id": 546873633,
        "sender_full_name": "Manuel Eberl",
        "timestamp": 1761305477
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The way we deal with this in Mathlib is <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MeasureTheory.AECover#doc\">docs#MeasureTheory.AECover</a>, and indeed most of the theory is done for countably generated filters.</p>",
        "id": 546874197,
        "sender_full_name": "Anatole Dedecker",
        "timestamp": 1761305686
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not claiming this is the most natural notion, I wrote it a while ago and with not a ton of mathematical background. Note that the way we get rid of the extra set <code>B</code> is that we put it in the measure (see e.g <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MeasureTheory.aecover_Icc_of_Icc#doc\">docs#MeasureTheory.aecover_Icc_of_Icc</a>)</p>",
        "id": 546874558,
        "sender_full_name": "Anatole Dedecker",
        "timestamp": 1761305796
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110031\">Patrick Massot</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/116395-maths/topic/Sequential.20convergence.20and.20countably.20generated.20filters/near/546871597\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I would guess the converse doesn’t hold, and search internet for examples of sequential spaces that are not first countable, hoping to find inspiration for counter-examples.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>There are lots of examples of spaces that are sequential, but not Frechet-Urysohn (and therefore not first countable). In particular, duals of infinite dimensional Montel Frechet spaces.</p>",
        "id": 546874914,
        "sender_full_name": "Moritz Doll",
        "timestamp": 1761305891
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>About convergence with sets, </p>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110031\">Patrick Massot</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/116395-maths/topic/Sequential.20convergence.20and.20countably.20generated.20filters/near/546871597\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I would guess the converse doesn’t hold, and search internet for examples of sequential spaces that are not first countable, hoping to find inspiration for counter-examples.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I also expect the converse to be false, but I'm not sure this is enough. I claim that if all neighborhoods filter of a space satisfy Manuel's condition then the space is Fréchet-Urysohn. </p>\n<p>Let me denote by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Seq}(\\mathcal{F})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Seq</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09931em;\">F</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> the sequentialization of a filter, namely the supremum over all sequences <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>u</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">u</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">u</span></span></span></span> converging to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{F}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09931em;\">F</span></span></span></span> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>u</mi><mo>∗</mo></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">u_*\\mathrm{atTop}_{\\mathbb{N}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9275em;vertical-align:-0.2441em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">u</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1757em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">atTop</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2381em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4559em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbb mtight\">N</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2441em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. Manuel's condition is then precisely <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Seq}(\\mathcal{F}) = \\mathcal{F}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Seq</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09931em;\">F</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09931em;\">F</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>But, in a topological space, one has <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>∈</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"script\">N</mi><mi>x</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mo>⟺</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mi>x</mi><mo>∈</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A\\in\\mathrm{Seq}(\\mathcal{N}_x) \\iff x\\in\\mathrm{SeqInterior}(A)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7224em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Seq</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14736em;\">N</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.1474em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⟺</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">SeqInterior</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>. Hence if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∀</mi><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"script\">N</mi><mi>x</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"script\">N</mi><mi>x</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\forall x, \\mathrm{Seq}(\\mathcal{N}_x) = \\mathcal{N}_x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∀</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Seq</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14736em;\">N</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.1474em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14736em;\">N</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.1474em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> we get that interior and sequential interior always coincide.</p>",
        "id": 546880461,
        "sender_full_name": "Anatole Dedecker",
        "timestamp": 1761307673
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think there is more hope to be found by looking for Fréchet-Urysohn spaces which are not first countable.</p>",
        "id": 546880620,
        "sender_full_name": "Anatole Dedecker",
        "timestamp": 1761307729
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay, thanks for all the replies! The AE cover looks like a good idea. I'll probably steal that.</p>",
        "id": 546885564,
        "sender_full_name": "Manuel Eberl",
        "timestamp": 1761309237
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>On a related note, there are two other things that are giving me some trouble: </p>\n<p>First, is a supremum of countably many countably generated filters again countably generated? I tried to prove it and I now suspect the answer is no.</p>\n<p>Second, can someone explain to me how the proof works that in a second countable linear order topology, <code>at_top</code> is countably generated?</p>",
        "id": 546886287,
        "sender_full_name": "Manuel Eberl",
        "timestamp": 1761309431
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"268315\">Anatole Dedecker</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/116395-maths/topic/Sequential.20convergence.20and.20countably.20generated.20filters/near/546880461\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>About convergence with sets, </p>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110031\">Patrick Massot</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/116395-maths/topic/Sequential.20convergence.20and.20countably.20generated.20filters/near/546871597\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I would guess the converse doesn’t hold, and search internet for examples of sequential spaces that are not first countable, hoping to find inspiration for counter-examples.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I also expect the converse to be false, but I'm not sure this is enough.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes, I’m sure it’s not enough, that’s why I wrote “hoping to find inspiration”.</p>",
        "id": 546888067,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Massot",
        "timestamp": 1761309899
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"233634\">Manuel Eberl</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/116395-maths/topic/Sequential.20convergence.20and.20countably.20generated.20filters/near/546886287\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>On a related note, there are two other things that are giving me some trouble: </p>\n<p>First, is a supremum of countably many countably generated filters again countably generated? I tried to prove it and I now suspect the answer is no.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Which order relation do you put on filters? Is it the Mathlib one or the wrong one?</p>",
        "id": 546888362,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Massot",
        "timestamp": 1761309995
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think it's the same one that Mathlib uses. Because the proof for countable infimum was trivial, and Mathlib has that one.</p>",
        "id": 546889711,
        "sender_full_name": "Manuel Eberl",
        "timestamp": 1761310363
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ok, then my guess is the result is wrong.</p>",
        "id": 546893212,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Massot",
        "timestamp": 1761311259
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"268315\">Anatole Dedecker</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/116395-maths/topic/Sequential.20convergence.20and.20countably.20generated.20filters/near/546880620\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think there is more hope to be found by looking for Fréchet-Urysohn spaces which are not first countable.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>here's some spaces</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>OnePoint ℚ</code></li>\n<li><code>OnePoint (Σ _ : ℝ, Unit)</code></li>\n<li><code>@Quot ℝ fun a b =&gt; a ∈ Set.range Int.cast ∧ b ∈ Set.range Int.cast</code></li>\n<li><code>@Quot (ℕ × OnePoint ℕ) fun a b =&gt; a.2 = OnePoint.infty ∧ b.2 = OnePoint.infty</code></li>\n<li><code>CofiniteTopology ℝ</code></li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 546893332,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1761311294
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It looks like it would require a countable product of countable sets to be countable.</p>",
        "id": 546893399,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Massot",
        "timestamp": 1761311315
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay that's what I thought. Thanks!</p>",
        "id": 546895759,
        "sender_full_name": "Manuel Eberl",
        "timestamp": 1761312034
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm having trouble coming up with a counterexample</p>",
        "id": 546895940,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1761312082
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>ok, looks like <code>⨆ i : ℕ, Filter.map (Prod.mk i) (Filter.atTop : Filter ℕ)</code> isn't countably generated</p>",
        "id": 546896640,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1761312290
    }
